41. Important Linux Commands and Concepts (Fundamentals → Advanced)

This section covers essential Linux commands and environment concepts that every SRE must understand. These commands are frequently used in production troubleshooting, automation, and system administration.

41.1 Running Processes in Background with nohup

The nohup command allows a process to continue running even after the user logs out of the terminal session.

This is useful in remote environments such as SSH sessions where disconnecting would normally stop running processes.

Basic syntax:

nohup command &

Example:

nohup cp -rf /etc /backup &

Explanation:

nohup prevents the process from stopping when the terminal closes.
cp -rf /etc /backup copies the directory recursively.
& runs the command in the background.

Output:

By default, output is written to:

nohup.out

Production use cases:

Long-running backups
Data migrations
Log processing
Batch jobs
Temporary automation tasks

Check the running process:

ps aux | grep cp

Monitor output:

tail -f nohup.out
41.2 Monitoring Commands with watch

The watch command runs another command repeatedly at a specified interval and displays the output in real time.

This is extremely useful during incidents and debugging.

Basic syntax:

watch command

Example:

watch df -h

This refreshes disk usage every 2 seconds.

Custom interval:

watch -n 1 command

Example:

watch -n 1 free -h

Real SRE use cases:

Monitoring memory during an incident.

watch -n 1 free -h

Monitoring Kubernetes nodes:

watch kubectl get nodes

Monitoring connections:

watch ss -s
41.3 Soft Links vs Hard Links

Linux allows files to be referenced using links.

There are two types:

Hard links
Symbolic links (soft links)

Hard Link

A hard link is another name for the same file inode.

Important characteristics:

Same inode
Cannot link directories
Must be on the same filesystem
If the original file is deleted, the hard link still works

Create a hard link:

ln file.txt hardlink.txt

Check inode:

ls -li

Example output:

123456 file.txt
123456 hardlink.txt

Same inode = same file.

Soft Link (Symbolic Link)

A symbolic link is a pointer to another file.

Create symbolic link:

ln -s file.txt symlink.txt

Check:

ls -l

Output example:

symlink.txt -> file.txt

If the original file is deleted:

The symlink becomes broken.

Production SRE usage:

Symbolic links are widely used in:

Application deployments
Version switching
Configuration management
Container images
Kubernetes volumes

Example:

/app/current -> /app/releases/v3

This allows instant rollbacks.

