41.7 The nmap Command (Network Scanning Tool)

nmap is used to discover hosts and services on a network.

It is widely used in:

Security analysis
Network debugging
Infrastructure discovery

Basic scan:

nmap localhost

Scan specific port:

nmap -p 80 localhost

Scan open ports:

nmap -p- server-ip

Service detection:

nmap -sV server-ip

Real SRE usage:

Understanding which services are running on a server during incident investigation.

Example:

A port unexpectedly open:

nmap production-server
41.8 /etc/profile

The file:

/etc/profile

Is a system-wide configuration file executed for login shells.

It defines environment variables and system settings for all users.

Common variables defined here:

PATH
USER
HOSTNAME
LANG

Example:

export PATH=$PATH:/usr/local/bin

This ensures commands in /usr/local/bin are available.

Important note for SREs:

Changes here affect all users in the system.

Reload:

source /etc/profile
41.9 /etc/bashrc

This file configures behavior for interactive bash shells.

It typically includes:

Aliases
Shell options
Prompt customization
Functions

Example:

alias ll='ls -la'

Difference between /etc/profile and /etc/bashrc

File	Purpose
/etc/profile	Login shell configuration
/etc/bashrc	Interactive shell configuration

Flow:

Login shell → loads /etc/profile
Interactive shell → loads /etc/bashrc

Understanding this is important when debugging environment issues.

41.10 $? — Exit Status of Last Command

The variable:

$?

Stores the exit code of the last executed command.

Example:

ls /tmp
echo $?

Output:

0

Meaning:

Command executed successfully.

If command fails:

ls /nonexistent
echo $?

Output:

2

This is extremely important in automation and scripting.

Example in scripts:

if [ $? -ne 0 ]; then
    echo "Command failed"
fi

Production SRE use:

Validating automation reliability.

41.11 $$ — Current Bash Process ID

The variable:

$$

Returns the PID of the current shell.

Example:

echo $$

Output:

21456

This is useful when:

Debugging scripts
Managing temporary files
Process tracking

Example:

tmpfile=/tmp/script_$$.log
41.12 The set Command

The set command controls shell behavior and displays environment variables.

Show all variables:

set

Important for debugging scripts.

Common production usage:

Enable strict mode in scripts.

set -e

Meaning:

Exit immediately if a command fails.

Advanced usage:

set -x

This prints commands as they execute.

Very useful in debugging automation pipelines.

Example:

set -ex
41.13 The unset Command

The unset command removes a variable or function.

Example:

MY_VAR=hello
unset MY_VAR

Check:

echo $MY_VAR

Output:

(empty)

Use cases:

Cleaning environment variables
Resetting shell state
Debugging configuration conflicts
